qualifications_and_interests.interest_in_serving:
I am interested in serving on this advisory board because I care deeply about how our city grows and changes, and I believe that thoughtful, inclusive planning can make a tangible difference in people’s daily lives. Having lived in Riverbend for over a decade, I have seen firsthand how decisions about zoning, transportation investments, and public spaces shape whether our neighborhoods remain affordable, welcoming, and connected—or whether they become places where long-time residents feel pushed out.

On a personal level, my commitment to this work is grounded in my own family’s experience. I grew up in a small town where my parents rented the same modest duplex for nearly twenty years. When I was in high school, our neighborhood was “rediscovered” and rapidly redeveloped. Our rent increased dramatically, and we eventually had to move to a more distant, car-dependent area. That experience of displacement—of feeling like decisions were being made about our community without our input—stayed with me and ultimately led me to pursue a career in urban planning. Serving on this advisory board is one way I can help ensure that other families have more of a voice in similar decisions.

From a professional standpoint, I recognize that advisory bodies play a critical role in bridging the gap between technical staff work and community values. I have seen, both as staff and as a commissioner, that the most effective advisory boards are those that:
1) Ask hard questions about who benefits and who may be harmed by a proposed policy or project;
2) Push for clear, accessible information so that community members can understand what is at stake; and
3) Take the time to listen to a wide range of perspectives, including those who may not show up to every public hearing.

I am particularly interested in helping the board:
- Advance housing affordability and stability, including strategies like missing middle housing, tenant protections, and community land trusts;
- Support small, locally owned businesses that reflect the cultural diversity of Riverbend;
- Improve transportation choices so people can safely and conveniently walk, bike, roll, or take transit;
- Integrate climate resilience into land use decisions, especially around tree canopy, heat islands, and flood-prone areas.

I also see this as an opportunity to continue learning and to share what I know. While I bring a strong background in planning, I am very aware that I do not have all the answers. I value learning from residents’ lived experiences, from colleagues in other disciplines, and from fellow board members who may come from very different professional or personal backgrounds. I am comfortable changing my mind when presented with new information, and I strive to be transparent about how I arrive at my recommendations.

Finally, I take the responsibilities of an advisory board member seriously: preparing thoroughly for meetings, disclosing potential conflicts of interest, respecting public input even when it is critical or emotional, and maintaining a clear distinction between my personal opinions and any official positions of the board. I am willing and able to commit the necessary time to read materials in advance, attend regular meetings and occasional special sessions, and participate in site visits or community events as needed. Serving on this board would be both a continuation of work I already care deeply about and an opportunity to contribute in a more focused and accountable way to the future of Riverbend.
